export const VOLUMES = {"I":{"title":"The shadow pictures, tinted silver and smoke","intro":"Classic noir is read as black-and-white, but the silver-nitrate frame is never neutral — it tilts warm toward tungsten or cool toward night, and the eye reads cigarette smoke, wet asphalt, and venetian-blind shadow as distinct greys. The palette is a near-monochrome with one or two tints doing all the work. Each refuses the flat black-and-white assumption: the noir frame is a tinted grey scale, not an absence of colour."},"II":{"title":"Three-strip Technicolor, saturated past life","intro":"Three-strip Technicolor produced colour more saturated and separated than reality — primary reds, emerald greens, and impossible skies, all under bright, even key light. The palettes are bold, clean, and joyful, with deep saturation as the whole point. Each refuses the muddy desaturated 'classic film' assumption: golden-age Technicolor is the most saturated colour cinema ever made."},"III":{"title":"The 1970s, warm, grainy, and underlit","intro":"The New Hollywood look came from fast film stock, available light, and a deliberate rejection of studio gloss — warm tungsten interiors, smoky browns, and underexposed shadow, with grain as a texture. The palettes are earthy and low-key. Each refuses the clean modern grade: the seventies frame is warm, dim, and amber, not crisp and cool."},"IV":{"title":"Imagined futures, cool, clean, and vast","intro":"Cinematic sci-fi tends to a controlled palette: sterile whites and blacks for the rational future, a single saturated accent for the technology, and vast cool fields for scale. The colour signals order, then breaks it with one hue. Each refuses the cluttered rainbow: the future on film is disciplined, usually monochrome-plus-one."},"V":{"title":"The dread pictures, where colour does the scaring","intro":"Horror uses colour as threat: an aggressive saturated hue against an otherwise muted field, or a sickly cast that makes the ordinary wrong. The structure is often a calm base violated by one alarming colour. Each refuses the generic dark-and-grey 'scary' look: the most frightening horror palettes are specific and often lurid."},"VI":{"title":"The frontier, sun-scorched and dust-blown","intro":"The Western lives in hard sunlight and dust: bleached sky, ochre earth, leather, and the deep shadow of a hat brim. Its palette is warm, dry, and high-contrast, set by the specific desert and stock used. Each refuses the generic 'sepia old-timey' wash: real Western grades are vivid ochre-and-blue or bleached white, not uniform brown."},"VII":{"title":"The Asian masters, where colour is composition","intro":"Across Hong Kong, mainland China, Korea, and beyond, a strain of art cinema treats colour as deliberate composition — saturated single-hue rooms, costume as palette, and light filtered through period detail. The colour is rich, controlled, and emotional. Each refuses the flat 'foreign film' assumption: these are among the most consciously colour-designed films ever made."},"VIII":{"title":"Drawn and rendered worlds, built colour by colour","intro":"Animation chooses every colour deliberately — there is no 'available light' to fall back on. The palettes are designed top-down for mood, from Ghibli's gentle naturalism to the neon of cyberpunk anime and the comic-book chromatics of modern CG. Each refuses the muddy realism of live action: animated colour is intentional, harmonised, and often joyful."},"IX":{"title":"Broken futures, drained of warmth","intro":"Dystopian cinema desaturates: grey-green institutional light, concrete, and steel, with colour appearing only as warning or as a rare remembered warmth. The palette signals a world where something human has been removed. Each refuses the vibrant blockbuster look: dystopia is muted on purpose, with one colour breaking through to mean hope or danger."},"X":{"title":"The storybook films, soft and symmetrical","intro":"A strain of contemporary cinema embraces candy pastels, warm symmetry, and nostalgic colour as a deliberate aesthetic — romance and whimsy made of millennial pink, butter yellow, and mint. The palettes are gentle, harmonised, and consciously charming. Each refuses the gritty realist grade: these films choose prettiness as meaning, not as decoration."},"XI":{"title":"The wide frame, where land is the lead","intro":"The landscape epic gives colour to scale: vast deserts, fields, and dunes shot in natural light where the land itself is the subject. The palettes are wide, warm, and elemental, with the human figure a small accent. Each refuses the busy, cut-up modern look: these films breathe in single huge fields of earth and sky."},"XII":{"title":"The neon night, where the city glows in the dark","intro":"Neo-noir trades the silver of classic noir for saturated neon: hot pink and electric cyan against wet black streets, the city lit by signage and screens. The structure is deep black violated by intense, artificial colour. Each refuses the muted realist night: these films are luminous, electric, and synthetic — colour as atmosphere itself."}};
